Differential gene expression DESeq2 of lung cancer and healthy patients

Elena Melnik

10 07 2021

This tutorial was made as part of the lessons “Differential gene expression” from GenomicsUa (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uV63nZWDB2U&ab_channel=NGOGenomicsUA)

Task: To determine which genes are expressed more strongly (RNASeq data analysis)

Introduction

Quantitative analysis of gene expression - analysis of the transcriptome, measurement of the transcriptional activity of a gene by determining the amount of its product, messenger RNA (mRNA), which is universal for most genes.

Expression Quantification with RNA-Seq As a result of RNA sequencing, a library of reads (or a library of reads) is created. First, the length of the read is determined from 25 to 200 nucleotides, depending on the selected sequencing method. Then the reads are mapped (or aligned) to the reference genome. Reads can be aligned to several genome regions at once or to different isoforms of the same gene.

As a result of the NGS analysis, we obtain raw data using the HTSeq software.

HTSeq A simple approach that counts the number of reads that intersect with a given genome. At the same time, the program contains various definitions of the intersection of a read with a gene.

This program allows us to get a quantitative signal or number of reads for each gene. We combine the number of reads for each sample into a table. And this table is further analyzed using differential gene expression analysis.

Models It is recognized that obtaining a reliable estimate of the variance parameter for each gene is critical for the analysis of expression indicators, and a lot of efforts have been concentrated in this direction. However, obtaining this is complicated by the small selection in most RNA-seq experiments, which motivates sharing information between genes for more accurate estimates. The first assumption was to assume that the variance parameter is the same for all genes, which allows it to be used using all the original data using the conditional extreme likelihood method. DESeq, edgeR, NBPSeq use gene data separation to estimate variance, are in the method. EdgeR uses a less restrictive approach - the variance of the definition for each gene, but individual estimates are “squeezed” to the total variance by the weighted likelihood method dgeR.

Most of the model parameters (baySeq, DESeq, edgeR, and NBPSeq) use the inverse binomial distribution model to explain the excess variance.

DESeq, edgeR, NBPSeq use the classic hypothesis testing approach. DESeq and NBPSeq derive an estimate of variance by modeling the observed relationship between mean and variance by parametric regression. DESeq uses a conservative approach - choose the largest value of the variance (from the estimate with the separation of information about other genes and estimate the variance for an individual gene).

It makes no sense to use the Poisson distribution because of the large variance, and in this case, it is the binomial negative one that is relevant.

Negative binomial distribution is a good fit for RNA-Seq data and flexible enough to account for biological variability.

DESeq Differential gene expression from count data based on negative binomial distribution. Offers two transformations for stabilizing the variance of count data - VST - Variance stabilizing Transformation - Regularizes log (rlog)

The raw data mustn’t be normalized before analysis since the normalization itself occurs in the program algorithm.

DESeq2 - Read counts associated with genes - Quality control Normalization Unsupervised clustering analyses - DE analysis Modeling raw counts for each gene Shrinking log2 fold changes Testing for differential expression

The NCI Genomic Data Commons database of lung cancer patients has been made publicly available here https://portal.gdc.cancer.gov/repository The file “Conditions” describes which samples are malignant and which are normal.

countData <- as.matrix(read.csv("LUSC_NORM.csv",row.names=2))
countData = countData[,c(2:10)]
colData <- read.csv("Conditions.csv", row.names=1)
all(rownames(colData) %in% colnames(countData))
## [1] TRUE

We get a composite dataset from raw gene expression data and a table that describes the samples. The resulting object can be used in other packages from Bioconductor.

Сreation a table with a new data type and perform a logarithmic transformation. In biostatistics, data are usually normalized logarithmically to reduce variance.

p-value and p.adjust are used to determine the significant difference in different samples

#create a new object to store information
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = countData, colData = colData, design=~condition, ignoreRank = TRUE)
## Warning in DESeqDataSet(se, design = design, ignoreRank): some variables in
## design formula are characters, converting to factors
#Applying the main function of this package to estimate statistical parameters
dds <- DESeq(dds)
## estimating size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing
#Filter out genes with less than 10 reads
keep <- rowSums(counts(dds)) >= 10
dds <- dds[keep, ]

#Extract results: p-values, p.adjust
res <- results(dds)

#what types of data are left
mcols(res, use.names=TRUE)

Setting the threshold and see how much of the given data is in object.

Depending on the problem, we choose a more or less stringent selection condition using p.adjust. The smaller this value, the smaller the sample of genes.

The average amount of normalized signal per gene. The point is the gene. The x-axis is the mean of normalized counts. The y-axis is the estimated variance. The variance of poorly expressed genes is higher.

#the number of genes at different p-values
sum(res$pvalue < 0.05, na.rm=TRUE)

Ploting the change in each gene between two categories: malignant and normal.

The line in the middle of the graph indicates the location of genes that remain unchanged, and moving up or down from it indicates more or less strong expression.

plotMA(res, ylim = c(-1,1))

Identifying colors using different shades of blue. Building a heat map.

The distance between cancerous and normal specimens is large. Clustering samples, building a dendrogram, combining the closest samples.

On the last heat map, we can see that the samples with cancer have greater differences than the normal ones. It can be caused by different mutations or different stages of the disease.

colours = colorRampPalette( rev(brewer.pal(9, "Blues")) )(255)
heatmap.2( sampleDistMatrix, trace="none", col=colours)

#isolation of the most variable genes in samples
topVarGenes <- head(order(rowVars(assay(rld)), decreasing=TRUE), 35)

#heatmap of the 35 most variable genes for both malignant and normal specimens
colours2=colorRampPalette( rev(brewer.pal(9, "RdBu")) )(255)
heatmap.2(assay(rld)[ topVarGenes, ], scale="row", trace="none", dendrogram="column",col = colours2)

Multidimensional plotting of differences between samples. Identifying the differences between groups in terms of “conditions”. We can see in the graph the grouping of samples with each other, groups of normal and malignant except for 1. The outlier may be a different type of cancer sample or a damaged sample.

#PCA - Principal component analysis
print( plotPCA(rld, intgroup = c( "condition")))

Discussion

Summing up the results of the differential gene expression analysis, we have identified the 35 most highly expressed genes and found on heatmap more and less expressed genes.
